'''Paul William Fletcher''' (born 16 January 1965) is an [[Australia|Australian]] politician, currently serving as [[Minister for Infrastructure and Regional Development (Australia)#List of ministers for urban development and cities|Minister for Urban Infrastructure and Cities]]<ref name="Turnbull2nd-4thAR">{{cite press release|quote=Paul Fletcher will take on an expanded role as Minister for Urban Infrastructure and Cities, charged with ensuring the Government’s infrastructure program meets its objectives of reducing congestion and improving the liveability of our cities. He will also continue the delivery of City Deals with state and local governments around the country.|url=https://www.pm.gov.au/media/ministerial-arrangements-2|title=Ministerial Arrangements|date=19 December 2017|publisher=[[Government of Australia]]|author=Turnbull, Malcolm|authorlink=Malcolm Turnbull|accessdate=3 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313005337/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/ministerial-arrangements-2#|archive-date=13 March 2018|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref> in the [[Second Turnbull Ministry]] and [[Morrison Ministry]] since July 2016. Fletcher has been a [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] member of the [[Australian House of Representatives]], representing the [[Division of Bradfield]], since his election to parliament at the [[Bradfield by-election, 2009|2009 Bradfield by-election]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://vtr.aec.gov.au/HouseDivisionFirstPrefs-14357-108.htm |title=NSW Division – Bradfield |work=Virtual Tally Room |publisher=[[Australian Electoral Commission]] |date=15 December 2009 |accessdate=24 August 2018 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091208102711/http://vtr.aec.gov.au/HouseDivisionFirstPrefs-14357-108.htm |archivedate=8 December 2009  }}</ref>

Fletcher served as the [[Parliamentary Secretary]] to the [[Minister for Communications (Australia)|Minister for Communications]] between September 2013 and September 2015 in the [[Abbott Ministry]], and between September 2015 and July 2016, he served as the [[Minister for Infrastructure and Regional Development (Australia)#List of ministers for major projects, territories, and local government|Minister for Major Projects, Territories, and Local Government]]. He briefly served as the [[Minister for Infrastructure and Regional Development (Australia)#List of ministers for regional development, territories and local government|Minister for Territories, Local Government and Major Projects]] between October and December 2017.

==Background and early career==
Fletcher was born in the English town of [[Devizes]] and came to Australia with his family at age two. He was a dual Australian/British citizen until 2009 when he renounced his British citizenship.<ref name="Salusinszky" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://paulfletcher.com.au/images/PFCitizenshipRenunciation.pdf|title=Paul Fletcher Citizenship Renunciation|accessdate=24 August 2018}}{{dead link|date=April 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>

Fletcher attended [[Sydney Grammar School]], before going on to earn first-class honours degrees in economics and law from the [[University of Sydney]]. In 1993 he was awarded a [[Fulbright Program|Fulbright Scholarship]] to go to [[Columbia University]]'s [[Columbia Business School|Graduate School of Business]] in New York City,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.paulfletcher.com.au/meet-paul/about-paul-fletcher|title=About Paul Fletcher|work=Paul Fletcher MP|access-date=2018-10-12|language=en}}</ref> where he completed a [[Master of Business Administration]] degree.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.australianchamber.com.au/profiles/the-hon-paul-fletcher-mp/|title=Australian Chamber of Commerce and IndustryThe Hon Paul Fletcher MP - Australian Chamber of Commerce and Industry|website=www.australianchamber.com.au|language=en|access-date=2018-10-12}}</ref>

In his early career, Fletcher worked as a management consultant, a corporate lawyer for [[Mallesons Stephen Jaques]], and a corporate strategist for TNT Limited. From 1996 to 2000, he worked as Chief of Staff to [[Minister for Broadband, Communications and the Digital Economy (Australia)|Minister for Communications]] [[Richard Alston (politician)|Richard Alston]], a Liberal Party politician. Fletcher joined Optus in 2000 and worked as Director of Corporate and Regulatory Affairs until 2008. He then founded Fletchergroup Advisers, a strategy consultancy focusing on the communications industry.<ref>Network Insight Institute (2009). [http://www.networkinsight.org/advisors/fletcher_paul.html Paul Fletcher] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050628031722/http://networkinsight.org/advisors/fletcher_paul.html |date=28 June 2005 }}. Retrieved 27 September 2009.</ref> He also wrote a book entitled ''Wired Brown Land? Telstra's Battle for Broadband'' that was published in 2009, discussing [[Telstra]]'s bid to operate the Australian Government's proposed [[National Broadband Network]].<ref>{{cite web | author1=Fletcher, Paul |title=Wired brown land : Telstra's battle for broadband |publication-date=2009|publisher=UNSW Press |isbn=978-1-74223-003-0 |url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/26412830}}</ref>

==Political career==
Fletcher was selected from a field of 17 people to be the Liberal Party candidate, following the retirement of former Liberal leader [[Brendan Nelson]]. Bradfield, a seat located in the [[North Shore (Sydney)|North Shore]] of Sydney, has been held continuously by the Liberal Party since its creation in 1949, and is one of the safest Liberal Party seats in Parliament. He was required to renounce his dual British citizenship prior to entering Parliament, as required by [[Section 44 of the Australian Constitution|Section 44]] of the [[Constitution of Australia]].<ref name=Cranston>{{cite news|last=Cranston|first=Belinda|title=UK executive pre-selected for Bradfield|date=27 September 2009|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|url=http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-national/uk-executive-preselected-for-bradfield-20090927-g7bi.html}}</ref> Fletcher had previously unsuccessfully sought Liberal Party pre-selection in the [[Division of Cook]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[Brisbane Times]] |date=3 August 2007 |url=http://news.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/nsw-liberals-reject-cook-candidate-towke-20070803-rdx.html |title=NSW Liberals reject Cook candidate Towke |accessdate=27 September 2009 }}</ref>

Under the Abbott government, Fletcher was the Parliamentary Secretary to the Minister for Communications. In September 2015 Fletcher was appointed as the Minister for Major Projects, Territories, and Local Government in the Turnbull government.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-09-20/turnbull-cabinet-reshuffle-whos-going-where/6775446|title=Turnbull cabinet reshuffle: who's going where |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|location=Australia|date=20 September 2015|accessdate= }}</ref> Fletcher has served as the Minister for Urban Infrastructure and Cities since July 2016.

==Personal life==
Fletcher is married to jeweller Manuela Zappacosta and they have one son, and they live with her son from a previous marriage.<ref name="Salusinszky" >{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/archive/news/ex-optus-exec-enters-politics/story-e6frgal6-1225780290620|title=Ex-Optus exec enters politics|last=Salusinszky|first=Imre|authorlink=Imre Salusinszky |date=28 September 2009|work=[[The Australian]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |date=27 September 2009 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/09/27/2697634.htm?section=justin |title=Fletcher an outstanding choice for Bradfield: Nelson |accessdate=27 September 2009 }}</ref>

